The area

Address
Neighborhood: City of London
From its ancient past as a Roman trading outpost to its 21st century status as the wealthiest square mile in the world, the financial district known simply as “The City” is one of London's most historic and fascinating neighborhoods. Here high rise office towers such as Norman Foster’s Gherkin mingle with Roman ruins and architectural marvels from virtually every era in between, including Christopher Wren's glorious St.Paul's Cathedral, and John Soane's dauntingly classicist Bank of England. This neighborhood is also home to some of the finest restaurants and plushest hotels in Europe, in addition to an assortment of watering holes, upscale shops, and Tube stations. During the week, the City is abuzz with white collar workers going about their business; the weekend sees this area turn into a quiet haven for sightseers.
How to get there
  • Monument • 5 min walk
  • Tower Hill • 5 min walk

    Nice views and well-maintained grounds
    Visited on a weekday during November 2023. No advance booking required. Breezed through security and onto the 15th floor, with practically no queues and no fuss. The grounds are well-maintained with good views over London. Although slightly obscured by taller buildings, the views are 360 degrees in an open air environment. Far less crowded in comparison to the nearby Sky Garden (which also requires advance booking). Would recommend.

  • Cheekycockney190757
    Basildon, United Kingdom11,485 contributions
    Wonderful addition to the City
    Visited twice in June 2023. Only found out it existed from a hidden gems TikTok, initially on a walk from Monument to Leadenhall Market then past the Lloyds Building to The Garden at 120. The second time straight from Fenchurch Street Station. No tickets/pre-booking are required, just rock up to a nondescript building with a large open area at the base and a wonderful animated ceiling. There is a security check and then you just queue to go up in the lift. There is a restaurant/cafe one floor down from the roof, but nothing on the actual roof though you can sit and eat whatever you bring I believe. The roof is decorated with flower beds, water features and seating. There are panoramic views all around, up and down the Thames, as well as the City/Gerkin. A wonderful/budget-friendly addition to any journey to the City.
    Visited June 2023

RTT
Washington37 contributions
Garden in the Sky
Sep 2024 • Solo
This location offers wonderful skyline views of London. I chose to visit this spot over its competitor (Sky Garden) because I love strolling through gardens. What better alternative than an actual garden in the sky?

I arrived at the Garden at 120 right when it opened, allowing me to enjoy a brief moment of peace before the crowds arrived. I had about 5 minutes of the rooftop to myself, and I cherish those minutes because, as soon as the next elevator of visitors arrived, the place quickly filled with people eager to take in the views.

The panoramic views were spectacular. You can spot landmarks like Tower Bridge, The Shard, Sky Garden, The Gherkin, and many more. You can also trace the Thames all the way to parts of Westminster. Truly a breathtaking sight!

Tips for future visitors:
1) Book your ticket in advance.
2) Go when it first opens, as I can imagine it gets crowded by the afternoon.
3) Bring a snack to enjoy at the top for a light picnic.
4) Bring a friend to share the experience.
5) Be respectful and dispose of litter properly.

Enjoy the views!
Written September 19, 2024
